## Set up Convex in Next.js

### 1. Install Convex and initialize the project
```
npm install convex
npx convex dev
```
- `npx convex dev` logs you in (browser OAuth), creates a Convex project, writes `NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL` to `.env.local`, and starts the **dev daemon** that syncs your `convex/` functions on every save.
- Keep `npx convex dev` running in a terminal tab while developing — it is the equivalent of `npm run dev` but for the backend.
- For new projects, you can also scaffold everything at once: `npm create convex@latest`.

### 2. Define your schema (`convex/schema.ts`)
```ts
import { defineSchema, defineTable } from 'convex/server';
import { v } from 'convex/values';

export default defineSchema({
  messages: defineTable({
    author: v.string(),
    body: v.string(),
  }),
  users: defineTable({
    name: v.string(),
    email: v.string(),
    tokenIdentifier: v.string(),
  }).index('by_token', ['tokenIdentifier']),
});
```
- `v` validators (`v.string()`, `v.number()`, `v.boolean()`, `v.id('tableName')`, `v.optional(...)`, `v.union(...)`) define the shape of each document.
- Every document automatically gets `_id` (typed `Id<'tableName'>`) and `_creationTime` (Unix ms timestamp).
- Indexes are declared on the table and queried with `.withIndex('by_token', q => q.eq('tokenIdentifier', token))`.
- The schema is enforced at runtime — insert/update will throw if a field doesn't match.

### 3. Write queries (`convex/messages.ts`)
```ts
import { query } from './_generated/server';
import { v } from 'convex/values';

export const list = query({
  args: {},
  handler: async (ctx) => {
    return await ctx.db.query('messages').order('desc').take(50);
  },
});

export const getById = query({
  args: { id: v.id('messages') },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    return await ctx.db.get(args.id);
  },
});

export const listByAuthor = query({
  args: { author: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    return await ctx.db
      .query('messages')
      .filter((q) => q.eq(q.field('author'), args.author))
      .collect();
  },
});
```
- Queries are **read-only** and automatically cached + resubscribed when underlying data changes.
- `ctx.db.query(table).order('asc'|'desc')` scans by `_creationTime`. Use `.withIndex(...)` for efficient field lookups.
- Return `null` for "not found" — Convex does not throw on missing documents, `ctx.db.get()` returns `null`.

### 4. Write mutations (`convex/messages.ts`)
```ts
import { mutation } from './_generated/server';
import { v } from 'convex/values';

export const send = mutation({
  args: {
    author: v.string(),
    body: v.string(),
  },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    const messageId = await ctx.db.insert('messages', {
      author: args.author,
      body: args.body,
    });
    return messageId;
  },
});

export const edit = mutation({
  args: { id: v.id('messages'), body: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    await ctx.db.patch(args.id, { body: args.body });
  },
});

export const remove = mutation({
  args: { id: v.id('messages') },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    await ctx.db.delete(args.id);
  },
});
```
- Mutations are **transactional** — if the handler throws, all writes in that call are rolled back.
- `ctx.db.insert(table, fields)` returns the new document's `Id`.
- `ctx.db.patch(id, fields)` does a partial update (like `UPDATE SET`). Use `ctx.db.replace(id, doc)` to overwrite the entire document.

### 5. Actions — for external API calls
```ts
import { action, internalMutation } from './_generated/server';
import { internal } from './_generated/api';
import { v } from 'convex/values';

export const sendWithNotification = action({
  args: { author: v.string(), body: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    // Actions CAN call external HTTP APIs
    await fetch('https://api.resend.com/emails', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.RESEND_API_KEY}`,
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      },
      body: JSON.stringify({
        from: 'noreply@example.com',
        to: 'admin@example.com',
        subject: 'New message',
        text: args.body,
      }),
    });

    // Then call a mutation to save (actions cannot write to DB directly)
    await ctx.runMutation(internal.messages.sendInternal, args);
  },
});
```
- Actions can make external HTTP requests; **queries and mutations cannot**.
- Actions must call mutations via `ctx.runMutation(api....)` or `ctx.runQuery(api....)` — they cannot access `ctx.db` directly.
- Set Convex environment variables in the dashboard: **Settings → Environment Variables**. Access them via `process.env.MY_KEY` inside actions.

### 6. Add ConvexProvider to Next.js App Router
Create `app/providers.tsx`:
```tsx
'use client';
import { ConvexProvider, ConvexReactClient } from 'convex/react';

const convex = new ConvexReactClient(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL!);

export function Providers({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <ConvexProvider client={convex}>{children}</ConvexProvider>;
}
```
Wrap it in `app/layout.tsx`:
```tsx
import { Providers } from './providers';

export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>
        <Providers>{children}</Providers>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```
- `ConvexProvider` must be a `'use client'` component — keep it in `providers.tsx`.
- `ConvexReactClient` is created once at module level, not inside a component.

### 7. Use real-time queries and mutations in components
```tsx
'use client';
import { useQuery, useMutation } from 'convex/react';
import { api } from '@/convex/_generated/api';

export function MessageList() {
  const messages = useQuery(api.messages.list);
  const send = useMutation(api.messages.send);

  // useQuery returns `undefined` while loading, then the data
  if (messages === undefined) return <p>Loading...</p>;

  return (
    <div>
      {messages.map((msg) => (
        <div key={msg._id}>
          <strong>{msg.author}:</strong> {msg.body}
        </div>
      ))}
      <button
        onClick={() => send({ author: 'Alice', body: 'Hello!' })}
      >
        Send
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```
- `useQuery` **auto-subscribes** — the component re-renders whenever the data changes in the database. No polling, no WebSocket setup.
- `useQuery` returns `undefined` (loading), `null` (query returned null), or the data.
- `useMutation` returns a function that you call with the mutation's args. It returns a Promise.
- Import paths use the auto-generated `api` object from `convex/_generated/api` — the structure mirrors your file names.

### 8. File storage
```ts
// convex/files.ts
import { mutation, query } from './_generated/server';
import { v } from 'convex/values';

// Step 1: Generate a short-lived upload URL
export const generateUploadUrl = mutation(async (ctx) => {
  return await ctx.storage.generateUploadUrl();
});

// Step 2: Save the storageId after the client uploads the file
export const saveFile = mutation({
  args: { storageId: v.id('_storage'), name: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    return await ctx.db.insert('files', { storageId: args.storageId, name: args.name });
  },
});

// Step 3: Retrieve a public URL for the stored file
export const getUrl = query({
  args: { storageId: v.id('_storage') },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    return await ctx.storage.getUrl(args.storageId);
  },
});
```

Client-side upload flow:
```ts
// 1. Get the upload URL from Convex
const uploadUrl = await generateUploadUrl();

// 2. POST the file directly to Convex storage
const result = await fetch(uploadUrl, {
  method: 'POST',
  body: file,
  headers: { 'Content-Type': file.type },
});
const { storageId } = await result.json();

// 3. Save the storageId in your database via mutation
await saveFile({ storageId, name: file.name });
```

### 9. Scheduled functions (cron jobs)
```ts
// convex/crons.ts
import { cronJobs } from 'convex/server';
import { internal } from './_generated/api';

const crons = cronJobs();

crons.daily(
  'send daily digest',
  { hourUTC: 8, minuteUTC: 0 },
  internal.emails.sendDailyDigest,
);

crons.interval(
  'clean up expired sessions',
  { minutes: 30 },
  internal.sessions.cleanup,
);

export default crons;
```
- Crons reference `internal.*` functions (not exposed to clients). Mark functions as internal by exporting from `_generated/api` using `internalMutation` / `internalAction` / `internalQuery`.

### 10. Deploy to production
```
npx convex deploy
```
- For CI, set `CONVEX_DEPLOY_KEY` as a secret (get it from Settings → Deploy Keys in the Convex dashboard).
- GitHub Actions example:
  ```yaml
  - name: Deploy Convex functions
    run: npx convex deploy --cmd 'npm run build'
    env:
      CONVEX_DEPLOY_KEY: ${{ secrets.CONVEX_DEPLOY_KEY }}
  ```

### Common errors & fixes
- **`NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL is not defined`** → `npx convex dev` was never run or `.env.local` is missing. Run `npx convex dev` to generate it.
- **`useQuery` returns `undefined` forever** → Either data is loading OR the function path is wrong. Verify the function is exported from the correct file and the `api.filename.functionName` path matches.
- **`Cannot destructure undefined`** → You destructured `useQuery` result without guarding for `undefined` (loading state). Always check `if (data === undefined) return <Skeleton />`.
- **`Argument validation failed`** → Args passed to the mutation/query don't match the `args:` validators. Check types and field names.
- **`Function not found` after editing**  → The dev daemon (`npx convex dev`) is not running. Restart it to sync function changes.
- **`ctx.db is not defined` in an action** → Actions cannot use `ctx.db` directly. Call `ctx.runQuery(api....)` or `ctx.runMutation(api....)` from the action.
- **`fetch is not a function` in a query** → Queries cannot make HTTP requests. Move the `fetch` call into an `action`.
- **Stale data after mutation** → `useQuery` updates automatically; if you're seeing stale data, check that you're using `useQuery` (not a one-time `fetch`). Manual refetching is never needed.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT call external APIs (`fetch`, `axios`) inside queries or mutations — only actions can make outbound HTTP requests. Queries/mutations must be deterministic and fast.
- Do NOT use `useQuery` in a Server Component — it requires the `ConvexProvider` React context and `'use client'`.
- Do NOT store secrets in `convex/` function source files — use Convex environment variables (dashboard → Settings → Environment Variables) and read them via `process.env.MY_KEY` inside actions only.
- Do NOT manually poll for data with `setInterval` or `setTimeout` — `useQuery` provides real-time updates automatically. Polling adds unnecessary read cost.
- Do NOT run `npx convex deploy` in CI without `CONVEX_DEPLOY_KEY` set — the deploy will fail silently or prompt for interactive login.
- Do NOT use `any` types for document IDs — use `v.id('tableName')` in args and `Id<'tableName'>` in TypeScript types for full type safety.
- Do NOT create mutations that call other mutations directly via `ctx.runMutation` inside a mutation — use a shared helper function instead, or combine the logic in one mutation to keep it transactional.
